SECTION 10: THE "EXPERIMENTAL" LAB (A/B TESTING WARFARE)
========================================================================
========
1. THE "SAMPLE SIZE" TRAP
- *Concept*: Stopping a test too early because "it looks like a winner."
- *The Elite Use*: Calculating "Statistical Power" before starting. If you need 10,000 users to
detect a 1% lift, and you stop at 5,000, your result is noise.
- *The "Peeking" Problem*: Repeatedly checking results increases the False Positive rate.
Use "Sequential Testing" frameworks (SPRT) if you must peek.
2. THE "NOVELTY EFFECT"
- *Concept*: Users click the new button just because it is new, not because it is better.
- *The Elite Use*: Run the test for at least 2 full business cycles (e.g., 2 weeks). Measure
"Long-Term Retention" of the change, not just immediate clicks. The novelty wears off; quality
remains.
